                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/12–844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-09T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 9, 1944—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10317. Personal for the Ambassador. With reference to your No. 10732, December 4,
                    midnight, we took this up again with the President and have received a statement
                    from him that he would be willing to accept a zone next to Bavaria, in other
                    words, a zone contiguous to the German zone which has been allocated to us. The
                    President desires, however, that we consult with the Joint Chiefs of Staff about
                    this before sending you further instructions. This we are doing urgently and
                    shall inform you promptly of the results.</p>
                <p>In the meantime, we have transmitted your No. 10864 of December 8 to the White
                    House and this message will no doubt serve to confirm the President’s present
                    inclination in this matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
